	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>A particle travels straight between the following pairs of points in <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
			</para>
			<para align="center">from <latex>P(1,1,0,0)</latex> to <latex>Q(0,0,1,1)</latex> to <latex>R(-1,2,1,3)</latex> to <latex>S(4,3,-2,2)</latex>
			</para>
			<para>Determine the total distance travelled by the particle.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach.ext>
			<solution.ext>
				<step>
					<pilot>
						<para>Express first how the individual legs of the trip add up to the total distance traveled.</para>
					</pilot>
					<para>We observe that the total distance traveled is the sum of three straight trips between pairs of points:</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>\text{dist}(P,Q) + \text{dist}(Q,R) + \text{dist}(R,S).</latex>
					</math.display>
				</step>
				<step>
					<pilot>
						<para>Next we compute the distance traveled on each of the straight trips</para>
					</pilot>
					<para>Now we compute the distance traveled between each pair of adjacent points of the trip:</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
							\begin{array}{rcl}
							\text{dist}(P,Q) & = & \sqrt{1+1+1+1}\ =\ 2 \\
							\text{dist}(Q,R) & = & \sqrt{1+4+0+4}\ =\ 3 \\
							\text{dist}(R,S) & = & \sqrt{25 + 1 + 9 + 1}\ =\ 6
							\end{array}
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</step>
				
				<step>
					<pilot>
						<para>We add the distance traveled on the straight segments up to obtain the total distance traveled.</para>
					</pilot>
					<para>So the total distance traveled by the particle is <latex>2+3+6=11</latex> [length units].</para>
				</step>
			</solution.ext>
		</approach.ext>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Find the corners of the square in the plane which is centered at the origin, has its edges parallel to the coordinate axes and whose diagonals have length <latex>4</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<solution>
				<para>We begin by determining the upper right corner <latex>(x,y)</latex> of the square. We know, its distance from the origin <subordinate>
					<hot>is <latex>2</latex>
					</hot>
					<info>
						<para>This information is given.</para>
					</info>
				</subordinate>. Next we observe that <latex>x = y</latex>. Therefore,</para>
				<para align="center">
					<latex>4 = x^2+y^2 = 2x^2</latex>, and so, <latex>x=y=\sqrt{2}</latex>.</para>
				<para align="center">
					<img src="ims/DistancePointsExrcs1_sltn.gif"/>
				</para>
			</solution>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Consider the solid disk in the plane whose center is <latex>C(1,1)</latex> and whose radius is <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>Plot the disk.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>
						<img src="ims/DistancePointsExrcs2_sltn.gif"/>
						
					</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>Find an equation whose solutions form the circle that appears as the boundary of the disk.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>Let  <latex>(x,y)</latex>  be a point in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>. Then <latex>(x,y)</latex>  belongs to the given circle exactly when its distance from  <latex>C</latex>  is <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>. This means</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>\text{dist}\left( (x,y),(1,1)\right)\ =\ \sqrt{(x-1)^2 + (y-1)^2}\ =\ \sqrt{2}.</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Squaring both sides yields the equivalent equation</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>(x-1)^2\ +\ (y-1)^2\ =\ 2</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>Find an inequality whose solutions form the entire disk, including its boundary.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>Let  <latex>(x,y)</latex>  be a point in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>. Then <latex>(x,y)</latex>  belongs to the given disk exactly when its distance from  <latex>C</latex>  is less than or equal to <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>. This means</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>\text{dist}\left( (x,y),(1,1)\right)\ =\ \sqrt{(x-1)^2 + (y-1)^2}\ \leq\ \sqrt{2}.</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Squaring both sides yields the equivalent equation</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>(x-1)^2\ +\ (y-1)^2\ \leq\ 2</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>Find an inequality whose solutions form the entire disk excluding its boundary.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>Let  <latex>(x,y)</latex>  be a point in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>. Then <latex>(x,y)</latex>  belongs to the given disk excluding its boundary exactly when its distance from  <latex>C</latex>  is less than <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>. This means</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex><![CDATA[ \text{dist}\left( (x,y),(1,1)\right)\ =\ \sqrt{(x-1)^2 + (y-1)^2}\ <\ \sqrt{2}. ]]></latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Squaring both sides yields the equivalent equation</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex><![CDATA[ (x-1)^2\ +\ (y-1)^2\ <\ 2 ]]></latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>Find an inequality whose solutions form the exterior of the disk excluding the boundary.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>Let  <latex>(x,y)</latex>  be a point in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>. Then <latex>(x,y)</latex>  lies strictly outside the given disk exactly when its distance from  <latex>C</latex>  is greater than <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>. This means</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex><![CDATA[ \text{dist}\left( (x,y),(1,1)\right)\ =\ \sqrt{(x-1)^2 + (y-1)^2}\ >\ \sqrt{2} ]]></latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Squaring both sides yields the equivalent equation</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex><![CDATA[ (x-1)^2\ +\ (y-1)^2\ >\ 2 ]]></latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
